# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-pinot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Kafka was originally developed at LinkedIn, and was subsequently open sourced in early 2011.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps, Neha Narkhede and Jun Rao helped co-create Kafka.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Graduation from the Apache Incubator occurred on 23 October 2012.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps chose to name the software after the author Franz Kafka because it is "a system optimized for writing", and he liked Kafka's work.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Apache Kafka is a distributed log-based messaging system that guarantees ordering within individual partitions rather than across the entire topic.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Unlike queue-based systems, Kafka retains messages in a durable, append-only log, allowing multiple consumers to read at different offsets.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Kafka uses manual offset management, giving consumers control over retries and failure handling.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] If a consumer fails to process a message, it can delay committing the offset, preventing further progress in that partition while other partitions remain unaffected.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] This partition-based design enables fault isolation and parallel processing while allowing ordering to be maintained within partitions, depending on consumer handling.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] In 2025, Apache Kafka introduced "Queues for Kafka", adding share groups as an alternative to consumer groups.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] This feature enables queue-like semantics where consumers can cooperatively process records from the same partitions, with individual message acknowledgment and delivery tracking.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Unlike traditional consumer groups where partitions are exclusively assigned, share groups allow the number of consumers to exceed partition count, making it ideal for work-queue patterns while maintaining Kafka's durability and scalability benefits.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] This development addresses the common challenge of "over-partitioning" that many Kafka users face.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Kafka Connect (or Connect API) is a framework to import/export data from/to other systems.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.9.0.0 release and uses the Producer and Consumer API internally.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] The Connect framework itself executes so-called "connectors" that implement the actual logic to read/write data from other systems.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Kafka Streams (or Streams API) is a stream-processing library written in Java.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.10.0.0 release.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] The library allows for the development of stateful stream-processing applications that are scalable, elastic, and fully fault-tolerant.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] The main API is a stream-processing domain-specific language (DSL) that offers high-level operators like filter, map, grouping, windowing, aggregation, joins, and the notion of tables.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Additionally, the Processor API can be used to implement custom operators for a more low-level development approach.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] The DSL and Processor API can be mixed, too.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] For stateful stream processing, Kafka Streams uses RocksDB to maintain local operator state.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] Because RocksDB can write to disk, the maintained state can be larger than available main memory.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] For fault-tolerance, all updates to local state stores are also written into a topic in the Kafka cluster.
[src:apache-pinot/apache-kafka] This allows recreating state by reading those topics and feed all data into RocksDB.
[src:apache-pinot/basics-concepts] Explore the fundamental concepts of Apache Pinot™ as a distributed OLAP database.
[src:apache-pinot/basics-concepts] Apache Pinot™ is a database designed to deliver highly concurrent, ultra-low-latency queries on large datasets through a set of common data model abstractions.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Apache Pinot is a real-time distributed OLAP datastore, built to deliver scalable real-time analytics with low latency.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] It can ingest from batch data sources (such as Hadoop HDFS, Amazon S3, Azure ADLS, Google Cloud Storage) as well as stream data sources (such as Apache Kafka).
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Pinot was built by engineers at LinkedIn and Uber and is designed to scale up and out with no upper bound.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Performance always remains constant based on the size of your cluster and an expected query per second (QPS) threshold.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] For getting started guides, deployment recipes, tutorials, and more, please visit our project documentation at https://docs.pinot.apache.org.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Pinot was originally built at LinkedIn to power rich interactive real-time analytic applications such as Who Viewed Profile, Company Analytics, Talent Insights, and many more.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] UberEats Restaurant Manager is another example of a customer facing Analytics App.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] At LinkedIn, Pinot powers 50+ user-facing products, ingesting millions of events per second and serving 100k+ queries per second at millisecond latency.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Pinot is designed to execute real-time OLAP queries with low latency on massive amounts of data and events.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] In addition to real-time stream ingestion, Pinot also supports batch use cases with the same low latency guarantees.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] It is suited in contexts where fast analytics, such as aggregations, are needed on immutable data, possibly, with real-time data ingestion.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Pinot works very well for querying time series data with lots of dimensions and metrics.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Want to join the ranks of open source committers to Apache Pinot?
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Then check out the Contribution Guide for how you can get involved in the code.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] If you have a bug or an idea for a new feature, browse the open issues to see what we’re already working on before opening a new one.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] We also tagged some beginner issues new contributors can tackle.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Share Your Pinot Videos with the Community!
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Have a Pinot use case, tutorial, or conference/meetup recording to share?
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] We’d love to feature it on the Pinot OSS YouTube channel!
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Drop your video or a link to your session in the #pinot-youtube-channel on Pinot Slack, and we’ll showcase it for the community!
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] For UI development setup refer this doc.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Normal Pinot builds are done using the `./mvnw clean install` command.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] However this command can take a long time to run.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] For faster builds it is recommended to use `./mvnw verify -Ppinot-fastdev`, which disables some plugins that are not actually needed for development.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] More detailed instructions can be found at Quick Demo section in the documentation.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] If you're building Pinot on macOS and encounter issues with the gRPC Java plugin during the build process, you may need to configure the protobuf Maven plugin to use a specific executable path.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] This is a known issue on macOS ARM (Apple Silicon) systems.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] You do **not** need to manually edit the `pom.xml` or set the plugin executable path.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] The correct profile will be selected based on your system and Homebrew installation.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] If you installed Homebrew to a non-default location, ensure the `protoc-gen-grpc-java` binary is available in either `/opt/homebrew/bin/` or `/usr/local/bin/`.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] If you encounter issues, check that the `protoc-gen-grpc-java` binary is present in one of the expected locations and is executable.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Please refer to Running Pinot on Kubernetes in our project documentation.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Pinot also provides Kubernetes integrations with the interactive query engine, Trino, and the data visualization tool, Apache Superset.
[src:apache-pinot/blob-readme-md] Check out Pinot documentation for a complete description of Pinot's features.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:apache-pinot/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:apache-pinot/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Apache Pinot is a real-time distributed OLAP datastore purpose-built for low-latency, high-throughput analytics, and perfect for user-facing analytical workloads.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Apache Pinot™ is a real-time distributed online analytical processing (OLAP) datastore.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Use Pinot to ingest and immediately query data from streaming or batch data sources (including, Apache Kafka, Amazon Kinesis, Hadoop HDFS, Amazon S3, Azure ADLS, and Google Cloud Storage).
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] We'd love to hear from you! to ask questions, troubleshoot, and share feedback.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] It's perfect for user-facing real-time analytics and other analytical use cases, including internal dashboards, anomaly detection, and ad hoc data exploration.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] User-facing analytics refers to the analytical tools exposed to the end users of your product.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] In a user-facing analytics application, all users receive personalized analytics on their devices, resulting in hundreds of thousands of queries per second.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Queries triggered by apps may grow quickly in proportion to the number of active users on the app, as many as millions of events per second.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Data generated in Pinot is immediately available for analytics in latencies under one second.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Pinot is designed to execute OLAP queries with low latency.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] It works well where you need fast analytics, such as aggregations, on both mutable and immutable data.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Pinot was originally built at LinkedIn to power rich interactive real-time analytics applications, such as , , , and many more. is another example of a user-facing analytics app built with Pinot.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Pinot can perform typical analytical operations such as slice and dice, drill down, roll up, and pivot on large scale multi-dimensional data.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] For instance, at LinkedIn, Pinot powers dashboards for thousands of business metrics.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Connect various business intelligence (BI) tools such as , , or to visualize data in Pinot.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] For analysts and data scientists, Pinot works well as a highly-scalable data platform for business intelligence.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Pinot converges big data platforms with the traditional role of a data warehouse, making it a suitable replacement for analysis and reporting.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] For application developers, Pinot works well as an aggregate store that sources events from streaming data sources, such as Kafka, and makes it available for a query using SQL.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] You can also use Pinot to aggregate data across a microservice architecture into one easily queryable view of the domain.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Pinot prevent any possibility of sharing ownership of database tables across microservice teams.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] Developers can create their own query models of data from multiple systems of record depending on their use case and needs.
[src:apache-pinot/docs-pinot-apache-org] As with all aggregate stores, query models are eventually consistent.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:apache-pinot/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
